        {
          year: '2001–present',
          title: 'Chronic instability — six presidents in seven years',
          spanish: 'la crisis política',
          body: 'Peru\'s 21st century has been a sustained crisis of political legitimacy. Since 2016, the country has had <strong>six different presidents in seven years</strong> — a degree of instability unmatched anywhere in the hemisphere outside acute civil conflict.<br><br>The pattern: <strong>Alejandro Toledo</strong> (2001-2006, first Indigenous-identifying president, later imprisoned for corruption). <strong>Alan García</strong> (his second term, 2006-2011, took his own life in 2019 as police arrived to arrest him for corruption). <strong>Ollanta Humala</strong> (2011-2016, also imprisoned for corruption). <strong>Pedro Pablo Kuczynski</strong> (2016-2018, forced to resign amid corruption allegations). <strong>Martín Vizcarra</strong> (2018-2020, impeached). <strong>Manuel Merino</strong> (2020, lasted five days before mass protests forced his resignation; two protesters killed by police). <strong>Francisco Sagasti</strong> (2020-2021, transitional). <strong>Pedro Castillo</strong> (2021-2022). <strong>Dina Boluarte</strong> (2022-present, as of 2025).<br><br>The structural drivers: the 1993 Fujimori-era constitution gives Congress extraordinary power to remove presidents via a "permanent moral incapacity" clause — and Congress has used it repeatedly. Corruption charges have entangled <strong>nearly every president since 2001</strong>, largely connected to the Brazilian construction firm <strong>Odebrecht</strong>, which bribed politicians across Latin America. Peruvian politics has become a perpetual war between executive and legislative branches, with citizens watching their leaders cycle in and out without ever resolving the country\'s underlying problems.<br><br>The most explosive recent moment: <strong>Pedro Castillo</strong>, a rural school teacher from Cajamarca who became Peru\'s first president from the Andean campesino class, won a narrow election in 2021. He had no governing experience, his government was chaotic, and Congress moved repeatedly to impeach him. On <strong>December 7, 2022</strong>, in a stunning act, Castillo announced he was dissolving Congress and ruling by decree — an attempted self-coup. It collapsed within hours. He was arrested. His vice president <strong>Dina Boluarte</strong> took office.<br><br>What followed in December 2022 and the first months of 2023 was the worst political violence in Peru in 30 years. Mass <strong>protests</strong> — overwhelmingly from the Andean south, supporting Castillo and demanding Boluarte\'s resignation and new elections — were met with brutal police and military repression. <strong>Roughly 60 protesters were killed</strong>, many in Puno and Ayacucho. Boluarte has been investigated for "genocide" but remains in office. Her approval ratings have fallen to roughly 5% — among the lowest in the world. Peru\'s next election is scheduled for 2026. What that election produces is anyone\'s guess.',
          vocab: ['la corrupción', 'la inestabilidad', 'el impeachment', 'la vacancia', 'la protesta', 'la represión', 'el campesino']
        },
        {
          year: 'The whole century',
          title: 'Peruvian writers, ceviche, and the cultural conversation',
          spanish: 'la cultura peruana',
          body: 'Behind and alongside the political chaos, Peru has produced one of the richest cultural traditions in the Spanish-speaking world.<br><br><strong>Mario Vargas Llosa</strong> (1936-2025) won the <strong>Nobel Prize in Literature in 2010</strong> — the second Latin American novelist to do so after García Márquez. His major novels — <em>La ciudad y los perros</em>, <em>Conversación en La Catedral</em>, <em>La fiesta del Chivo</em>, <em>La guerra del fin del mundo</em> — have shaped global understanding of Latin American politics, dictatorship, and society. He was also a defining political intellectual: a leftist in his youth (close to Cuba\'s revolution), then increasingly liberal in the European sense, then a center-right presidential candidate against Fujimori in 1990. His ideological evolution — from Sartre-influenced engagement to a defense of Hayek-style classical liberalism — became its own subject of study. The novelist died in 2025.<br><br><strong>José María Arguedas</strong> (1911-1969) is the great Andean novelist — bilingual in Spanish and Quechua, raised in the highlands, deeply attuned to Indigenous Peru in ways that Lima-based writers were not. His novel <em>Los ríos profundos</em> (1958) is a masterpiece of literature about cultural division and belonging. He took his own life in 1969, having spent his career trying to give literary voice to a Peru most of his fellow writers couldn\'t see.<br><br><strong>César Vallejo</strong> (1892-1938), from the northern Andes town of Santiago de Chuco, is widely considered one of the greatest Spanish-language poets of the 20th century. His books <em>Los heraldos negros</em> and <em>Trilce</em> reinvented Spanish-language poetry. He died in Paris, poor.<br><br>And then there\'s the <strong>food</strong>. Peruvian cuisine has, since roughly 2000, become one of the most globally celebrated culinary traditions in the world. <strong>Ceviche</strong> — raw fish "cooked" in lime juice with red onion, ají, and salt — is the national dish (it has its own holiday, June 28). <strong>Lomo saltado</strong> blends Chinese stir-fry technique with Andean ingredients — a literal cultural fusion that emerged from Chinese immigrants to Peru in the 19th century (who also gave Peru the word <em>chifa</em> for Chinese-Peruvian restaurants). <strong>Ají de gallina</strong>, <strong>causa</strong>, <strong>anticuchos</strong>, <strong>cuy chactado</strong>, <strong>pachamanca</strong>, the chocolate of the Amazon, the potatoes of the high Andes (Peru has over <strong>4,000 native potato varieties</strong>) — Peru\'s culinary heritage is the product of five thousand years of Andean agriculture, Spanish colonial cooking, African influence, Chinese and Japanese immigration, and Italian and Lebanese arrivals.<br><br>Lima\'s restaurants now consistently rank among the world\'s best. Chef <strong>Gastón Acurio</strong> has been a deliberate cultural ambassador, using cuisine to project Peruvian identity globally in a way Peruvian politics never has.<br><br>And musically: <strong>huayno</strong> (Andean folk), <strong>marinera</strong> (the coastal national dance), <strong>chicha</strong> (Andean migration music born in Lima\'s shantytowns), <strong>Afro-Peruvian music</strong> (preserved by figures like Susana Baca and Eva Ayllón) — a sonic landscape as varied as the geography itself.',
          vocab: ['la literatura', 'el Premio Nobel', 'el novelista', 'el poeta', 'la gastronomía', 'el ceviche', 'el chifa', 'el huayno']
        }
