          body: 'At the far southern edge of the Maya world, in what is today western Honduras, stood the city of <strong>Copán</strong>. Founded around 100 CE and at its height between 400 and 800 CE, Copán was a center of Maya astronomy, sculpture, and dynasty. Its <strong>hieroglyphic stairway</strong> — over 2,200 carved glyphs — is the longest single Maya inscription known.<br><br>The Copán dynasty ruled for sixteen successive kings. The most celebrated, <strong>K\'inich Janaab Pakal\'s contemporary 18 Rabbit</strong> (Uaxaclajuun Ub\'aah K\'awiil, ruled 695-738), commissioned much of the city\'s monumental sculpture before being captured and beheaded by a rival from nearby Quiriguá. The city declined in the 9th century, like other classic Maya centers, but the descendants of its builders still live in the region.<br><br>Copán\'s ruins are a <strong>UNESCO World Heritage Site</strong> and one of the most studied Maya sites in the world. Its sculptures are extraordinarily three-dimensional compared to other Maya cities — Copán was the high point of classic Maya stone carving.',
