          title: 'Contras, dictators, and the 2009 coup',
          spanish: 'los contras y el golpe de 2009',
          body: 'In the 1980s, under President <strong>Ronald Reagan</strong>, Honduras became the staging ground for the US-backed <strong>Contras</strong> who were fighting to overthrow the Sandinista government in neighboring Nicaragua. Honduran territory was used to base, train, and arm them. The country received massive US military aid; it also developed its own death squads (notably <strong>Battalion 3-16</strong>), which targeted leftists, students, and union organizers.<br><br>In 2009, a constitutional crisis exploded into a coup. President <strong>Manuel "Mel" Zelaya</strong> — a wealthy rancher who had drifted leftward and joined the Latin American "pink tide" — proposed a nonbinding poll on whether to convene a constitutional assembly. The military and conservative establishment, with the Supreme Court\'s backing, sent soldiers to his house in pajamas at dawn and put him on a plane to Costa Rica. The Organization of American States and most countries condemned the action as a coup.<br><br>The post-2009 government, eventually led by the National Party, faced widespread protests and accusations of widespread corruption — culminating in <strong>former president Juan Orlando Hernández being extradited to the United States in 2022 on drug-trafficking charges</strong>; he was convicted in 2024.',
