          title: 'Hurricanes, MS-13, and the migration caravans',
          spanish: 'huracanes, pandillas y las caravanas migratorias',
          body: '<strong>Hurricane Mitch</strong> in October 1998 was the deadliest Atlantic hurricane in two centuries — and it sat over Honduras for days. Mitch killed over 7,000 Hondurans, displaced 1.5 million, and destroyed an estimated 70% of the country\'s crops and infrastructure. The country has never fully recovered. In 2020, Hurricanes <strong>Eta and Iota</strong> hit within two weeks of each other, devastating the same regions again.<br><br>Beginning in the 1990s, MS-13 (Mara Salvatrucha) and Barrio 18 — gangs founded in Los Angeles by Central American refugee youth, then deported back to countries they barely knew — exploded in Honduras and El Salvador. For years Honduras had one of the highest homicide rates in the world. Entire neighborhoods became no-go zones controlled by gangs that extorted businesses, schools, and households.<br><br>The combination — climate disaster, gang violence, corruption, poverty — produced the <strong>migrant caravans</strong> that became a global news story starting in 2018. Tens of thousands of Hondurans (and others) walked north in groups for safety. Migration from Honduras to the US continues at historic levels. In 2022, voters elected the country\'s first woman president, <strong>Xiomara Castro</strong> — Mel Zelaya\'s wife — promising reform. Her government has faced enormous structural obstacles and continued violence.',
